Dr. King, thank you for being an influence in my life, changing the way we think about those around us and for making America a better place to live. #ILSOS #MLK50 #MLK #MLK50Forward #MLK50NCRM @TheKingCenter @NCRMuseum  7/7

Dr. King demonstrated to me how one man with a dream could affect society and improve the quality of life for untold millions. I will continue to carry his teachings with me and allow them to guide me to be the best person I can be, and I urge others to do the same.  6/7
I espouse his philosophies to my Tumblers, reminding them to love their fellow men and women, to never discriminate against or dislike someone because of their race, color or creed.  5/7

It is through the lens of Dr. King’s wisdom that I have forged my path in public service, establishing the Jesse White Tumblers nearly 60 years ago as a way to give back to the community and help those in need of guidance.  4/7
During my time there, I attended a small church and was taken under the wing of a local pastor. That pastor was Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.  3/7

I first met the Reverend when I was a student at Alabama State University in 1954. My move as a student on an athletic scholarship from Chicago to the segregated city of Montgomery, Alabama brought challenges and frustrations due to the racial climate in the South.  2/7

As we remember Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. on the 50th anniversary of his assassination, I think of all the good he did for our society and on a personal level what he meant to me in shaping my life.  1/7
